.TH RMD "1" "May 2026" "202605011146-git" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
rmd \- Remove files and directories recursively
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B rmd
[\fI\,OPTIONS\/\fR] [\fI\,FILE\/\fR]...
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B rmd
is a script for safely removing files and directories recursively. It includes safety checks to prevent accidental deletion of critical system files and directories.
.PP
The script protects against common mistakes like wildcard deletions at root level.
.SH INPUT MODES
Paths to delete may be supplied in any of the following ways, and the modes can be combined freely:
.IP \(bu 2
\fBPositional arguments\fR \(em \fBrmd\fR \fIfile1\fR \fIfile2\fR. Standard usage; the shell expands any wildcards before \fBrmd\fR sees them
.IP \(bu 2
\fBSingle\-quoted glob patterns\fR \(em \fBrmd\fR \fI'~/Test/*.log'\fR. The script itself performs leading\-tilde and glob expansion, so the kernel \fBARG_MAX\fR limit (which would otherwise trigger \fIArgument list too long\fR on huge expansions) is avoided
.IP \(bu 2
\fBStdin\fR \(em \fBfind\fR \fI.\fR \fB\-name\fR \fI'*.bak'\fR \fB|\fR \fBrmd\fR \fB\-\-yes\fR. When standard input is not a tty, each non\-empty line is treated as an additional path. Stdin is merged with any positional arguments
.PP
The combination of quoted\-glob expansion and stdin handling lets users delete arbitrarily large file lists without ever exceeding \fBARG_MAX\fR.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-\-force
Override the soft block on system\-path wildcards (e.g. \fB/var/log/*\fR). Has \fBno effect\fR on the hard\-block list documented in \fBSAFETY GUARDS\fR
.TP
.BR \-\-yes
Skip the 2 second cancel\-deletion delay before each removal
.TP
.BR \-\-dir " " \fI\,PATH\/\fR
Set the working directory before processing arguments
.TP
.BR \-\-help
Display help message with usage information and available options
.TP
.BR \-\-config
Generate or regenerate user configuration file with default settings
.TP
.BR \-\-version
Show script version information and exit
.TP
.BR \-\-options
Display all available command\-line options
.TP
.BR \-\-debug
Enable debug mode with verbose output and command tracing (set \-x)
.TP
.BR \-\-raw
Disable colorized output for plain text display
.SH SAFETY GUARDS
.PP
The following are \fBalways refused, even when --force is supplied\fR:
.IP \(bu 2
\fB/\fR (the root filesystem). When invoked from a tty, the user is prompted whether they meant the current directory (\fB$PWD\fR) and on confirmation the deletion is retargeted there. Non\-interactive callers are refused outright with a hint
.IP \(bu 2
\fB/etc\fR, \fB/bin\fR, \fB/usr/bin\fR, and the user's \fB$HOME\fR (the protected parent directories themselves)
.IP \(bu 2
\fB/etc/passwd*\fR, \fB/etc/group*\fR, \fB/etc/shadow*\fR, \fB/etc/gshadow*\fR (system identity files, including their \fB.bak\fR / \fB-\fR variants)
.PP
\fBSpecific named paths\fR under protected parents are allowed and unaffected by these guards \(em e.g. \fB/etc/myfile.bak\fR, \fB/etc/nginx/*\fR, \fB~/MyDir\fR, \fB~/Test/*\fR. Other top\-level system directories (\fB/var\fR, \fB/tmp\fR, \fB/usr\fR, etc.) are refused as soft blocks; \fB--force\fR does \fInot\fR override their parent\-self refusal but does override system\-wildcard literals like \fB/var/log/*\fR.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B rmd directory/
Remove a directory and its contents
.TP
.B rmd file1 file2
Remove multiple files
.TP
.B rmd '~/Test/*.log'
Single\-quoted glob \(em the script expands the tilde and pattern internally
.TP
.B find . -name '*.bak' | rmd --yes
Stream paths from stdin, skipping the cancel delay
.TP
.B rmd --force '/var/log/*.gz'
Override the soft system\-wildcard block (still cannot delete \fB/etc\fR, identity files, or \fB/\fR)
.SH FILES
.TP
.B ~/.config/myscripts/rmd/settings.conf
User configuration file for rmd preferences
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success
.TP
.B 1
General error
.TP
.B 2
Dangerous operation prevented
.SH NOTES
.IP \(bu 2
Includes safety checks to prevent catastrophic deletions
.IP \(bu 2
Prevents wildcard deletions at root level
.IP \(bu 2
Wrapper around rm with additional protections
